default2default              defaultTo what extent are the needs of defaultdifferent groups of passengers (e.g. people with disabilities, older people, young people) taken into account in determining the provision of public tradefaultnsport to isolated communities?default&#xa0;default2.1
default              
defaultLack of access to transport is a huge issue for many people living 
defaultin rural areas. For those families where there is only one
default, or no
default, vehicle
default and/or limited public transport, it can restrict access to key services such as healthcare
default, education, social activities,
default etc. 
defaultThis particularly impacts on women especially with you
defaultng children.  
default2.2
default              
defaultAccess to support groups for those facing discrimination or other challenges is much more difficult as the groups tend to operate within the larger towns. This particularly impacts on the LGBT community and those with disabilities includ
defaulting people with mental health challenges and those experiencing domestic violence or other forms of harassment.
default2.3
default              
defaultLiving in rural areas poses particular challenges for people with disabilities in accessing education, training, and employment opportunitie
defaults and playing an active role in their communities. Access to transport is crucial and voluntary sector provision or adapted taxis are often very expensive.
default2.4
default              
defaultEvidence shows considerable variability in the provision and availability of services between di
defaultfferent rural 
defaultareas but
default overall, the picture is of under-provision and they are less likely to receive services comparable with their urban counterparts.
default For example, older people in rural areas are likely to receive lower levels of supportive services su
defaultch as domiciliary care and meals on wheels than those living in urban areas, and the general take-up rates for welfare benefits seem lower.
default2.5
default              
defaultYoung people are also significantly 
defaultdisadvantaged
default: whilst they are taken into account where there is a statutory
default requirement e
default.
defaultg
default.
default getting people to school, there is no provision to allow young people to take part in 
defaultextracurricular
default activities and other social networking as they can’t get home afterwards or 
defaulttravel at weekends.  This also impacts on their ability to take part in further training and job search and limits employment opportunities to those accessible by public transport which significantly reduces their opportunities. 
