default6default              defaultWhat are the main challenges associated with funding transport services in isolated communities? How can these services be made more affordable?default&#xa0;default6.1
default              
defaultThe main challenge is to overcome the “we’ve always done it this way approach”
default to the provision of
default rural transport. 
defaultWhilst the economic downturn has resulted in a relatively rapid withdrawal of financial support for bus services that had previously seen escalating costs, with little potential for passenger growth; little has been done
default to date
default either in
default South Somerset or nationally to look at options that can mitigate the impact
default of local bus service provision
default often for those groups with the most need. 
default The concept that we have outlined above 
defaultoffers a potential solution to this issue. 
default&#xa0;
default6.2
default              
defaultThe low 
defaultpopulation density in most of these areas means
default that the cost per passenger is likely to be high when compared with 
defaultmost
default urban routes. As 
defaultindicated
default above 
defaulttypically all types of Community Transport schemes have evolved on an ad hoc basis to meet 
defaultthe needs o
defaultf their community,
default often in response to the decline or withdrawal of local bus services. Laudable as this is their very nature means they often operate in isolation from each other and 
defaultpublic transport operators. Closer liaison
default means that savings could
default oft
defaulten
default be
default made by the
default CT
default operators and
default with the added potential of increasing patronage on core routes.
default 
default&#xa0;
